Project: No Shows Appointments¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This project aims at predicting if people show up for their appointments or not. It is important for the understanding of patients' behaviour and their reasons for not showing up for their scheduled medical appointments. I chose this project because I have seen many doctors and hospital staffs suffer with the issue of rescheduling and cancelling appointments. It kills a lot of their time and energy. With this analysis, I feel it would be easy for them to schedule appointments keeping in mind the patients' behaviour.

Parameters Used - 'PatientId', 'AppointmentID', 'Gender', 'ScheduledDay', 'AppointmentDay', 'Age', 'Neighbourhood', 'Scholarship', 'Hipertension', 'Diabetes', 'Alcoholism', 'Handcap', 'SMS_received', 'No-show'

The following questions are answered through this project -¶

  1. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on the day of a week?
  2. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on day of the month?
  3. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on the month?
  4. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on his/her gender?
  5. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on his/her age?
  6. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on how far the hospital is from his/her residence?
  7. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on reminder messages?
  8. Does the showing up of a person for a scheduled appointment depends on which medical problem he is experiencing?
  9. Are the patients helped and motivated by the government scholarship funds to visit hospitals for checkup?
  10. What factors determine the person's showing up for a scheduled appointment?

Steps to clean and prepare data for building a predictive model¶

  1. Variable Identification

#convert to datetime64[ns]
df['ScheduledDay'] = df['ScheduledDay'].apply(np.datetime64)
df['Day_Scheduled'] = df['ScheduledDay'].dt.day
df['weekday_Scheduled'] = df['ScheduledDay'].dt.dayofweek
df['Month_Scheduled'] = df['ScheduledDay'].dt.month


df['AppointmentDay'] = df['AppointmentDay'].apply(np.datetime64)
df['Day_appointed'] = df['AppointmentDay'].dt.day
df['weekday_appointed'] = df['AppointmentDay'].dt.dayofweek
df['Month_appointed'] = df['AppointmentDay'].dt.month

def CreateBarGraph(list1, color1):
    plt.figure(1)
    cols = list1
    colour = color1
    i = 0
    for col in cols:    
        plt.subplot(int(str(22)+str((cols.index(col)+1))))
        df[col].value_counts(normalize=True).plot.bar(figsize=(20,15), fontsize = 10.0, color = colour[i])
        plt.title(col +' vs count%', fontweight="bold", fontsize = 22.0)
        plt.ylabel('Count %', fontsize = 20.0)
        plt.xlabel(col, fontsize=20.0)
        i = i +1

#to create dist and box plot
def dist_box_plot(param,title1,y1):
    plt.figure(1)
    plt.subplot(121)
    sns.distplot(df[param]).set(title=title1, ylabel=y1)
    plt.subplot(122)
    df[param].plot.box(figsize=(16,5))
    plt.title(title1)
    plt.ylabel(y1)
    plt.show()

Feature Engineering¶

To gain more information from the data

Variable Transformation¶

It is typically meant to change scale or adjust skewed data distribution. The given dataset doesn't require any kind of such changes.

Variable Creation¶

It is the step where we require to form a new variable which could ease the task information extraction from data. In this dataset, we created new columns to store date in datetime64 format and not in string format.

Removing unnecessary columns¶

We don't need to consider all the given columns for the analysis. Columns containg patientid of the people and their appointmentid are unnecessary. We must drop those before data exploration.

In [46]:

    range_df['age'] = range(100) 
    Male_Hyper = range_df.age.apply(lambda x:len(df[(df.age == x) & (df.gender == 'M') & (df[col] == 1) & (df.noshow == 'No') ]))
    Female_Hyper = range_df.age.apply(lambda x:len(df[(df.age == x) & (df.gender == 'F') & (df[col] == 1)& (df.noshow == 'No')]))

    # multiple line plot
    plt.plot( range_df, Male_Hyper, marker='o', markerfacecolor='blue', markersize=2, color='skyblue', linewidth=4)
    plt.plot( range_df, Female_Hyper, marker='', color='olive', linewidth=2)

    plt.legend(['Male','Female'])
    plt.xlabel('Age')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('Gender based difference w.r.t Age - For {} patients'.format(col));

Inference ->¶

  • More males in the age group 40-80 suffering from hypertension and diabetes show up for appointments in comparison to females of same age.
  • Alcoholic patients from Male group visits are more compared to female in range from 45 to 65.
  • Not much difference in male and female visits for hansicap patients.

LIMITATIONS¶

  1. The given dataset had data for only 3 months because of which we can not confidently say that most of the people visit doctors in the month of may.
  2. The number of reminder msgs sent of the patients are not known to determine the number of times a patient needs to be reminded for his/her appointment.
  3. Data for the number of patients at a particular place is not known. Because of this, we can't say why most of the people are coming from Jardim Camburi.
  4. The amount of scholarship given is not known. So, we can't determine why a certain of people even after getting the scholarship do not show up.

CONCLUSION¶

  1. 25% people even after recieving the scholarship did not visit.

  2. Hypertension and Diabetes patients are attending the doctor when compared to other medications. Age ranges from 40 to 80 - with females conversion is better than Males.

  3. Majority of the people in age group 20-40 did not show up for appointments.

  4. Female patients are not active in getting appointments in comparison to men of same age.

  5. Most of the appointments are on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday.

  6. More alcoholic male patients of age 45-65 have showed up in comparison to females of same age.

  7. Most of the visits are from Jardim Camburi. This might be possible that most of the patients are from that area or the hospitals are nearby that place. Complete data to confidently say this is not provided.

  8. If more number of reminders are sent, then more people might visit for their appointments. Considering, 25k people who received reminders visited.
